---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema, medicalWebPageSchema } from '../../../../data/schema.js';

const title = '9–12 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress';
const description = 'Between 9 and 12 months, babies reach major developmental milestones including pulling to stand, early walking, saying "mama" and "dada," pointing, and following simple instructions.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is it normal if my 12-month-old is not walking yet?',
    answer: 'Yes. While many babies take their first steps around their first birthday, the typical range for walking independently is 9–15 months (CDC, 2022). As long as your baby is pulling to stand, cruising along furniture, or standing alone, motor development is progressing. If your baby is not standing with support at all by 12 months, mention it to your pediatrician.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should my baby say their first word?',
    answer: 'Most babies say their first intentional word between 10 and 14 months (CDC, 2022). By 12 months, most babies use simple gestures like shaking their head "no" or waving "bye-bye," which are as developmentally important as spoken words at this stage. If your baby has no words and no gestures at 12 months, discuss it with your pediatrician.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my baby to be afraid of strangers at this age?',
    answer: 'Yes. Stranger anxiety and separation anxiety typically peak between 9 and 12 months (CDC, 2022). Your baby is beginning to understand that they are a separate person from you and may become clingy or cry when you leave or when someone unfamiliar approaches. This is a sign of healthy emotional attachment and cognitive development.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the pincer grasp and why is it important?',
    answer: 'The pincer grasp is the ability to pick up small objects using the thumb and index finger. This milestone typically develops around 9–10 months (CDC, 2022). It is a major fine motor milestone — it allows babies to self-feed small pieces of food and eventually leads to skills like holding a pencil and using tools.',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/9-12-months/milestones/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
const mSchema = medicalWebPageSchema({
  name: title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/9-12-months/milestones/',
});
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  medicalSchema={mSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: '9–12 Months', href: '/ages/9-12-months/' },
    { label: 'Milestones' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>9–12 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress</h1>

  <p>The window between 9 and 12 months is a period of remarkable transformation. Your baby is transitioning from infant to toddler — moving from relative stillness to exploring their environment with new mobility and communication skills. This is the age of firsts: first steps, first words, and the first birthday.</p>

  <h2>What social and emotional milestones should I expect at 9–12 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 12 months, most babies show clear preferences for familiar people, engage in simple interactive games like peek-a-boo and pat-a-cake, exhibit separation anxiety when a caregiver leaves, and begin to cooperate with dressing by putting out an arm or leg (CDC, 2022). Social referencing — looking to a trusted caregiver's face for cues about how to react in new situations — is also well-established by this age.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Stranger anxiety:</strong> May be shy, anxious, or fearful around strangers. This is a sign of healthy attachment.</li>
    <li><strong>Separation anxiety:</strong> May cry when a parent leaves the room or during childcare drop-off. Typically peaks at 9–10 months.</li>
    <li><strong>Preferences:</strong> Has favorite people and toys; may hand you a book when they want to hear a story.</li>
    <li><strong>Attention-seeking:</strong> Repeats sounds or actions to get your attention or a laugh.</li>
    <li><strong>Cooperation:</strong> Puts out an arm or leg to help with dressing.</li>
    <li><strong>Social games:</strong> Plays simple interactive games like peek-a-boo and pat-a-cake.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What communication milestones should my 9–12 month old reach?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 12 months, most babies say "mama" and "dada" specifically to their parents, understand the word "no," use simple gestures like shaking their head and waving bye-bye, and point to direct your attention to things they find interesting (CDC, 2022). Pointing — especially declarative pointing (pointing to share something, not just to request it) — is one of the most important milestones of this stage.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Understanding "no":</strong> Responds to simple spoken requests and understands "no" even if they do not always follow it.</li>
    <li><strong>Gestures:</strong> Uses simple gestures like shaking their head "no" or waving "bye-bye."</li>
    <li><strong>Vocalization:</strong> Makes sounds with changes in tone, sounding more like real speech.</li>
    <li><strong>First words:</strong> Says "mama" and "dada" specifically to their parents and may say exclamations like "uh-oh."</li>
    <li><strong>Pointing:</strong> Points at objects of interest to share them with you — a major social-communication milestone.</li>
    <li><strong>Imitation:</strong> Tries to repeat words or sounds that you say.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What cognitive milestones should I look for at 9–12 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 12 months, most babies find hidden objects easily, use objects functionally (drinking from a cup, brushing their hair), bang objects together to hear the sound, and follow simple one-step directions like "Give me the ball" (CDC, 2022). Object permanence — the understanding that things exist even when out of sight — is now fully established.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Object permanence:</strong> Finds hidden objects easily. Understands that toys still exist under a blanket.</li>
    <li><strong>Functional use:</strong> Begins using objects correctly — drinking from a cup, trying to brush their hair.</li>
    <li><strong>Cause and effect:</strong> Bangs two things together to hear the sound. Drops items to watch them fall.</li>
    <li><strong>Pincer focus:</strong> Pokes with their index finger and uses the pincer grasp to pick up small items.</li>
    <li><strong>Following directions:</strong> Follows simple one-step directions like "Please give me the ball."</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What gross motor milestones should my 9–12 month old be reaching?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 12 months, most babies pull to stand using furniture, cruise along furniture while holding on, and many can briefly stand alone or take a few independent steps (CDC, 2022). Some babies are not walking independently until 13–15 months — this is within the typical range. The most important sign of healthy gross motor development is progression: each week, your baby should be doing a bit more.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pulling to stand:</strong> Pulls themselves up to stand using furniture.</li>
    <li><strong>Cruising:</strong> Walks while holding onto furniture.</li>
    <li><strong>Standing alone:</strong> May stand for a few seconds without holding on.</li>
    <li><strong>First steps:</strong> May take a few steps without holding on, though many babies do not walk until closer to 15 months and this is typical.</li>
    <li><strong>Getting to sitting:</strong> Gets into a sitting position without help from an adult.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 9–12 Month Milestones</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When should I talk to my pediatrician about my 12-month-old's milestones?</h2>
    <p>The CDC and AAP recommend developmental screening at the 9-month and 12-month well-child visits. Talk to your pediatrician if your 12-month-old:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does not crawl or seems to drag one side of their body while crawling</li>
      <li>Cannot stand when supported</li>
      <li>Does not search for things that they see you hide</li>
      <li>Does not say single words like "mama" or "dada"</li>
      <li>Does not learn gestures like waving or shaking their head</li>
      <li>Does not point to things</li>
      <li>Has lost skills they once had</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Developmental regression — losing skills a child once had — is always a reason to call your pediatrician promptly. Early intervention services (available in every U.S. state for children under 3) are most effective when started early.</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
